<HL>
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<LP>
   DOW JONES INDUSTRY GROUPS were calculated with an
incorrect price for BankAmerica Corp. stock Thursday. Using
the stock's correct closing composite price of $30 a share,
the money center banks industry group index for Thursday
should be 186.45; the financial sector index should be
284.48, and the Dow Jones Equity Market Index should be
332.56.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   DIGITAL SYSTEMS INTERNATIONAL'S National Market System
short position in the month to mid-June was 34,415 shares,
not the 1,914,090 shares listed in Wednesday's edition. The
incorrect number was due to a reporting error by a Nasdaq
member firm, and reduced total NMS short interest for the
period to about 256.5 million shares.
   ---
   OLIN Corp. expects changes in its mix of businesses and
certain other factors to contribute to strong second-half
earnings that should result in full-year profit at the lower
end of the company's per-share target range of $6 to $6.40.
Friday's edition reported Olin's expectation that
second-quarter earnings would decline 15% to 20% from the
1989 period's record level, but didn't mention the outlook
for the second half and full year.
   (See: "Abreast of the Market: Industrials Rise 16.58 as
Investors Buy Firms With Proven Earnings" -- WSJ June 29,
1990)
   ---
   VSB BANCORP Inc. expects to report a third-quarter pretax
loss of $2.5 million, which will result in "several hundred
thousand dollars" of savings on an after-tax basis, according
to a spokesman. Friday's edition failed to note the $2.5
million loss was before taxes.
   (See: "Business Brief -- VSB Bancorp Inc.: Savings Bank
Parent Sees $2.5 Million 3rd-Period Loss" -- WSJ June 29,
1990)
   ---
   GRANT STREET NATIONAL BANK is an independent, publicly
held company. In Friday's edition, Grant Street National was
incorrectly identified as a unit of Mellon Bank Corp.
   (See: "Mellon's Grant Street Unit" -- WSJ June 29, 1990)
</TEXT>
