</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0178
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0178.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dylex Holders Clear
   Authorizing Preferred
   Usable to Pay Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18
</SO>
<CO>
   T.DLX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Holders of Dylex Ltd. approved the
authorization of a new class of convertible preferred shares
that could be used instead of cash to pay off 150 million
Canadian dollars (US$128.4 million) of debentures
outstanding.
   Holders of the 9.25% debentures can retract them at 110%
of their face value in 1992. The retailing company can ill
afford such a cash outlay. Dylex had losses of C$10.5 million
for the quarter ended May 5 and C$60.7 million for the fiscal
year ended Feb. 3. But the company has the option of
substituting the new securities for cash.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Wilfred Posluns, chairman and chief executive officer,
said Dylex nevertheless would like to avoid issuing the newly
authorized shares, because they could dilute the company's
widely held Class A nonvoting shares, into which the
preferred would be convertible.
   He said Dylex might consider raising cash through the sale
of a division or real estate, share issues by a division, or
borrowing against real estate. But he said no specific plans
had been made for any of these measures.
   In trading Friday on the Toronto Stock Exchange, Dylex
Class A shares closed unchanged at C$3.95 (US$3.38).
</TEXT>
