<HL>
   International -- Washington Insight:
   Wary of a NATO Overhaul, U.S. Hopes
   To Keep West From Conceding Too Much
   ----
   By Gerald F. Seib
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The White House is beginning to worry that
proposals to make the Western alliance more palatable to the
Kremlin and to the Western public are moving too fast.
   When the North Atlantic Treaty Organization meets in
London this week, talk of extensive change in the alliance
will be in the air, and President Bush will be cheerleading
for change. But behind the scenes, Mr. Bush is determined to
keep the process from turning into a reckless rush.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   West Germany has floated a host of ideas to alter the
basic tenets of the alliance that has existed for more than
four decades. When NATO leaders meet in London, everything
will be open to change: defense strategy on the ground, the
positioning of nuclear weapons and the makeup of Western
military forces.
   In addition, the U.S. is prepared to discuss with its
allies eventually withdrawing U.S. nuclear-tipped artillery
shells from West Germany unilaterally, the Washington Post
reported Sunday. Such a withdrawal would be designed to
counter Soviet calls for complete denuclearization of
Germany. The White House wouldn't confirm the report.
   But U.S. officials fear the West may be hurrying into
other commitments that would cut troop levels in a united
Germany too deeply. They also are concerned that too much
loose talk of nuclear withdrawals will incite public clamor
to remove all short-range nuclear weapons from Germany before
agreements on such weapons can be negotiated with Moscow.
   So the president and his men are saying the NATO meeting
merely should start the process of changing the alliance,
rather than complete the job. This is a tricky position for
the U.S. to take because it raises the risk of a clash with
West German leaders, who are eager to accommodate Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev so he will let the united Germany
belong to NATO. The Bush administration, which has been
working assiduously to develop a special relationship with
the emerging new Germany, doesn't want to alienate Germans
now.
   The U.S. shares the general German goal; indeed, Mr. Bush
himself called the NATO summit to pave the way for a new
Germany's membership in the alliance. U.S. and German
officials already have agreed on broad outlines for how to
change NATO. Specifically, they have agreed in principle on
the idea of thinning NATO's front-line troops and putting
them under multinational commands rather than under
individual member countries.
   The NATO meeting is likely to bless such a change, which
would fundamentally overhaul Western defense strategies and
set up a defense structure that could be shrunk as East-West
tensions ease. In addition, the NATO meeting will lay plans
to begin negotiations to shrink NATO's nuclear arsenal and
perhaps adopt language for a historic non-aggression
agreement between NATO and Warsaw Pact nation.
   Yet the U.S. also wants to be sure that it doesn't
emasculate NATO, the one European organization in which the
U.S plays a dominant role. The U.S. sees a NATO with muscle
as essential to its hopes to retain political, economic and
military influence in the emerging Europe.
   U.S. officials are worried about West Germany's new
willingness to promise the Soviets specific reductions in the
united German army as part of the conventional-arms agreement
now being negotiated in Vienna. While the U.S. and West
Germany, until recently, agreed that they should offer the
Soviets some general pledge to shrink the German army after
unification, they resisted negotiating the extent of the
reduction until the conventional-arms treaty is finished and
follow-up talks with the Soviets begin.
   Now, U.S. officials say, Bonn is suggesting that a
specific pledge be made by inserting in the conventional-arms
pact a formula defining how many troops any Central European
country can maintain. U.S. officials don't want to commit the
West to a specific troop level before military planners have
calculated the size and configuration of the new NATO.
   In addition, while the U.S. has promised to stop
modernizing NATO's arsenal of short-range nuclear missiles
and shells and to start negotiating cuts in the stockpile,
Mr. Bush and his aides want to squelch any talk that NATO
might scrap its policy of reserving the right to be the first
side to use nuclear weapons.
   The U.S. considers the first-use option necessary to guard
against a conventional attack. More importantly, it worries
that a no-first-use pledge would help generate public
pressure to pull all nuclear weapons out of Germany without
waiting for an orderly negotiating process.
   Britain and France, which don't want the public pressing
them to get rid of their own nuclear arsenals, share the U.S.
sentiment. So this week's meeting, Secretary of State James
Baker suggests, "will simply kick off a review" of how the
West will negotiate cuts in short-range nuclear arms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0148
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0148.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   EPA Bans Mercury
   From Indoor Paint;
   Poisoning Is Cited
   ----
   By Rose Gutfeld
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6C
</SO>
<IN>
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<GV>
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Citing a risk of poisoning, the
Environmental Protection Agency is banning mercury from
indoor paint and requiring outdoor paint that contains it to
carry warning labels.
   The requirements take effect Aug. 20. For paint already on
store shelves, the National Paint and Coatings Association is
working with manufacturers to place labels indicating that
any interior paint containing more than 200 parts per million
of mercury should be used only outside. While EPA officials
recommended at a briefing that consumers avoid paints with
mercury, the officials said consumers could safely use up
existing interior paint with less than 200 parts per million
of mercury as long as they ventilate thoroughly and minimize
exposure of children.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mercury is in 25% to 30% of all indoor latex paint to keep
it from spoiling while in the can. It's in about 20% to 35%
of all exterior latex paint to prevent mildew. Oil-based
paint doesn't contain mercury. Linda Fisher, an assistant EPA
administrator, said the industry will bear about $40 million
to $50 million in costs of reformulating paint, with
additional expense possible for manufacturers unable to sell
their existing stocks. For consumers, paint prices are likely
to rise about 1%.
   In a statement Friday, the paint association said it would
cooperate with the EPA, even though the association doesn't
believe "there is any scientific evidence to give consumers
any cause for alarm about use of interior products currently
on the market."
   The EPA became concerned about mercury in paint when a
four-year-old Michigan boy last year came down with a rare
form of poisoning, after paint containing mercury was used in
his home. Symptoms of this childhood mercury poisoning
include severe pain in the extremities, sweating and a rapid
heart beat. Other symptoms include slight tremors of the
hands, short-term memory loss and headaches.
   EPA officials urged people who have painted recently with
a mercury-containing paint to ventilate the area thoroughly.
The agency released a list of paint manufacturers that use
mercury and companies that don't. Consumers who want to know
whether a specific paint contains mercury can call
1-800-858-7378, a toll-free number at the National Pesticide
Telecommunication Network.
   The agency said it believes that the mercury concentration
in air decreases within a few days after painting, but that
lower concentrations may be present for months. People
wishing to dispose of paint containing mercury should consult
community hazardous-waste programs or local governments for
the proper ways to do so. Mercury shouldn't be poured down
drains, or into any bodies of water, since it is toxic to
many species, the EPA said.
   The EPA action results from a voluntary agreement worked
out with the companies that produce mercury for use in
paints. These companies are continuing to provide data that
the EPA will use to determine whether further action is
warranted for outdoor paint, or for such products as
spackling and joint compounds, which also contain mercury.
   Most pesticide uses of mercury were banned in 1976. At the
time, the agency allowed mercury's continued use in paint
because good alternatives weren't available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0147
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0147.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   On the Record:
   Iraq Weighs
   Threat of War
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<LP>
   The following are excerpts from an interview with Saddam
Hussein, president of Iraq, by Karen Elliott House of the
Journal. They enlarge on issues discussed in Ms. House's
article on page one of this newspaper Thursday. A related
editorial appears nearby.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   How has the end to the Cold War affected the Mideast?
   The positive side is much greater than the negative
impact.
   The positive side is that this will make the Arab nation
one single share and not two to be divided between two
superpowers. . . . America can no longer say Arabs are tools
of the Soviet Union.
   The negative side is that it is now clear the U.S. can
exert influence on the Soviets and make them abandon any
position contrary to the U.S. So the U.S. thinks it can cast
things any way it wants in the region and in alliance with
Israel can suppress any voice in support of Arab rights. So,
the U.S. has tilted more towards Israel. This is a very grave
change.
                                                                                                       

   Can Egypt sit out a war?
   Peace is the prevailing theme in the Arab world for all
Arabs. Any Arab who wants to defend his rights should not be
interpreted as not desiring peace. Egypt is part of the Arab
world.
   If war were to break out as a result of the expansionist
policy of Israel it is only natural that this will be fought
by all Arabs. . . . (I)f fighting continues for a long time
no Arab individual shall remain capable of remaining outside
the circle of contribution to confrontation with Israel.
   Israel is accustomed in other wars to snatching quickly
from Arabs valuable objectives and this has helped Israel in
maintaining its expansionist policies.
   So if Israel were to conduct an aggression, then the con-
frontation must be long. This is the view of Iraq and Arabs
have no different view. Once the fighting continues for a
long time the outcome will be different. It will not be what
Israel desires.
                                                                                                       

   How can there be a long war when Israel possesses nuclear
weapons?
   Arabs do have new weapons which may be sufficient for
confronting this small population (Israel) if it were to
commit aggression against the larger population.
                                                                                                       

   Do you mean chemicals can deter nuclear weapons?
   Yes, I believe chemicals constitute a deterrent. Why
should the U.S. fail to voice concern when they and others
helped Israel possess nuclear weapons? When I said if Israel
attacks Iraq with nuclear weapons then Iraq would respond
with chemicals, all hell was raised and still is being
raised.
   This has been treated as a threat. It is as if the
objective was that Arabs should accept that Israel has
nuclear weapons and can dictate the situation and Arabs
should abandon all their rights.
                                                                                                       

   Are you seeking a nuclear capability?
   It has neither been in our program nor is it now in our
program to use these for military purposes.
   Iraq is in possession of binary chemical weapons. Our
scientists and technicians and military men calculate that
this is sufficient to deter an Israeli nuclear weapon. If the
U.S. were to lend us nuclear weapons with the objective of
striking a balance with the nuclear weapons given Israel, we
shall not decline them.
                                                                                                       

   Do you expect more terrorism?
   The U.S. went through a war to create an independent union
and civilians were killed. So let us address human issues on
a single standard. We cannot talk about those deprived of
basic rights as terrorists. The U.S. attacked the house of
(Libyan leader Moammar) Gadhafi with women and children
inside. The raid killed civilians. Is this terrorism? If
Palestinians conduct an attack in the occupied territories,
if such Palestinians are regarded as terrorists, we have to
regard the president of the United States as the greatest
terrorist.
                                                                                                       

   Is war inevitable?
   The U.S. is not prepared to sacrifice anything for peace
in the area. Does the U.S. feel it is doing us a favor just
talking to the PLO? It is the PLO that is doing the U.S. a
favor. It is opening a dialogue with a country whose bias is
clear for Israel.
   It is the duty of the U.S. to make peace comprehensive.
The U.S. should give up the evil ideas of the Zionist lobby
including the false view that the U.S. cannot guarantee oil
supplies without Israel in the region to insure that.
                                                                                                       

   What is your oil strategy?
   Oil is $14 a barrel now, one half the real level of 1971.
This price does not respond to the true value. Who is
responsible for this injustice? Western countries. Isn't this
a conspiracy against the economy of the region? We do not
want to use oil as a political weapon. . . . But nobody can
eliminate the significance of economics in political
relations.
                                                                                                       

   What are prospects of a final peace with Iran?
   We are conducting direct dialogue with the Iranians and
each party has told the other that we are placing great hopes
on this dialogue achieving the desired objectives. So my hope
is great that peace will come about between Iran and Iraq.
                                                                                                       

   Why do you call on U.S. ships to leave the Persian Gulf?
   We were not consulted by the U.S. when the ships were
brought in, but we didn't fight their presence because some
of our Arab brothers under the existence of Iranian
aggression saw it proper that U.S. ships should be allowed.
But now that East-West relations have achieved such a
positive level and now that the Iraq-Iran War is over, we
cannot see how the presence of U.S. ships can be interpreted
for positive reasons. Ask the U.S. what are the reasons for
their presence other than conducting intelligence on Arabs
for Israel or creating a naval military situation between
Iraq and Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0146
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0146.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Line of Recognition
   Equipment Marks
   Shift in Strategy
   ----
   By Hal Lancaster
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6D
</SO>
<CO>
   REC PROSZ
</CO>
<IN>
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Recognition Equipment Inc. will introduce soon a
series of products aimed at the computer imaging market,
company officials said.
   The new products represent a shift in strategy for the
company, which is trying to reshape its own image after a
string of quarterly losses and a host of litigation. As part
of that shift, Recognition Equipment is divesting itself of
some operations to focus its attention on image processing,
systems that enable companies to automate the handling of
paperwork.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The products to be introduced fall into three categories.
One category will enable users to create and modify their own
image processing systems without requiring sophisticated
programming knowledge. The second will enable users to enter
images and data from documents into the system. The third is
made up of workstation products that enable each user to
program the system to handle specific work applications.
Recognition Equipment can sell customers products in each
category or bundle them into a complete system.
   Recognition Equipment has been involved in optical
scanning products for some time. But in the past few months,
the company has shifted its strategic focus from developing
specific, proprietary systems to industry-standard products
that can be adapted to any customer's equipment, said Tom
Hurley, co-chief executive officer.
   The company also is approaching the market differently,
Mr. Hurley said, by teaming with computer makers and systems
integrators to develop complete systems for customers. As an
example, he cited the proposal the company submitted with
Wang Laboratories Inc. to provide a large state agency with
an imaging system that would automate the handling of tax
forms. In other projects, the company is teaming with
companies such as International Business Machines Corp. and
Andersen Consulting.
   Mr. Hurley said Recognition Equipment is focusing its
marketing attention on systems for government agencies and
transportation, insurance and financial services companies,
all of which handle large amounts of documents. But it hopes
to gain business in other market niches through its partners.
   Bob Vanourek, co-chief executive, said that the company is
looking at the possibility of selling assets that contribute
about $100 million in sales annually, but that only the
Postalogic division, which makes mail reading and sorting
systems, has been sold. Because of the difficulty in finding
financing sources these days, he said, the sale of assets
hasn't progressed as quickly as hoped. And he said the
company isn't under any pressure to sell and may choose to
operate the divisions as autonomous units if adequate bids
don't emerge.
   Mr. Vanourek wouldn't project earnings, but said the
company is "getting close" to returning to profitability. For
the first half ended April 30, the company had a net loss of
$13 million, wider than the $490,000 loss a year earlier.
   Mr. Vanourek also noted that the company increased its
cash balances to $45 million at the end of the second quarter
from about $25 million a year earlier, and attracted some
significant new outside institutional investors. He also
estimated that the company's work force has shrunk about 11%
to about 2,200 in recent months, and said the major staff
reductions "are behind us."
   Messrs Hurley and Vanourek were installed as co-chief
executives late last year under an agreement with Prospect
Group, a leveraged buy-out firm that attempted to take over
Recognition Equipment. New York-based Prospect owns a 14%
stake in the company. Recognition has been mired in eight
civil lawsuits relating to a 1988 indictment that accused the
company and two of its top officers with attempting to
manipulate the award of $400 million in U.S. Postal Service
contracts. In November, a federal judge acquitted all
defendants in the case; since then, Mr. Vanourek said, the
company has settled most of the major litigation stemming
from the indictments.
</TEXT>
