<HL>
   Technology:
   Pressure Rises
   For New Accord
   On Cut in CFCs
   ----
   By Richard L. Hudson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- The ink is barely dry on a world
ozone-protection agreement reached here, but political
pressure for tougher measures is already mounting.
   The United Nations-sponsored pact calls for the developed
world to ban chlorofluorocarbons and many other
ozone-destroying chemicals by the year 2000. The developing
world has an extra decade to comply. The accord, expected to
cost the U.S. economy about $4.5 billion, is aimed at halting
chemically caused damage to the atmosphere's natural layer of
ozone gas, which helps block the Sun's harmful ultraviolet
rays.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the London agreement won't be the last word on the
subject. Even as the 10-day meeting ended Friday, officials
from West Germany, Australia, Scandinavia and other
"green"-minded nations were pushing for tougher measures --
including a ban by 1997, instead of 2000. And
environmentalists and some leading ozone scientists
immediately denounced the accord as inadequate to protect the
ozone layer.
   "Within five years' time, they {world governments} will
realize they have to go a lot faster" to end use of CFCs,
said Joseph C. Farman, a British scientist whose discovery of
an "ozone hole" over Antarctica in 1985 touched off the
global alarm over CFCs. The accord, Mr. Farman said, will
still allow a 33% rise over the next decade in the
atmospheric concentration of ozone-destroying chlorine
compounds -- with unpredictable results for human health.
   The prospect of tougher curbs worries many
chemical-industry officials, who say even the 2000 deadline
will be difficult to meet. "It's crystal ball-gazing," said
Michael Harris, a lobbyist for Britain's Imperial Chemical
Industries PLC. The accord "is an act of faith that somehow
or other our industry will find the answers to meet that
timetable."
   The world's $2 billion-a-year production of CFCs and
related chemicals are used in refrigerators, air
conditioners, foam insulation, spray cans and industrial
solvent compounds. Many of these uses can be avoided; for
instance, nations can easily replace CFCs with hydrocarbon
gases as spray-can propellants, as U.S. industry did by law
in 1978.
   But industry officials say that at least 40% of today's
CFC uses will depend for substitutes on special
ozone-friendly chemicals that the industry is only now
developing, many of which won't be ready until the middle of
the decade.
   Most of the measures adopted in London -- which must still
be ratified by each nation's legislature -- are already in
U.S. House and Senate drafts of the Clean Air Act in
Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0137
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0137.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Amerada Hess Unit
   In Deal to Buy
   Placer Dome Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   AHC PDG T.POC
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Amerada Hess Corp. said a Canadian company
owned jointly by its Amerada Minerals Corp. of Canada Ltd.
subsidiary and by Poco Petroleums Ltd. of Canada, agreed to
purchase a Canadian oil and gas company for 305.5 million
Canadian dollars (US$260 million).
   The companies will purchase Placer Cego Petroleum Holdings
Ltd. from Placer Dome Inc., Vancouver. Placer Cego has
producing properties and exploration acreage principally in
British Columbia and Alberta. It also operates nine gas
producing plants.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cash-rich Placer Dome said the sale is expected to close
Sept. 27 and should generate a "favorable" special gain to
Placer Dome and inflate its cash holdings to more than C$1
billion, its spokesman said. He wouldn't estimate the size of
the gain.
   Placer Dome, a major gold producer, has never regarded oil
and gas as a core business. The company put all of its
Canadian and U.S. energy assets up for sale in December,
after receiving what it termed unsolicited expressions of
interest. In May, Placer Dome announced a pact to sell its
U.S. oil and gas unit, Houston-based Prairie Producing Co.,
to Los Angeles-based Unocal Corp., for $336 million including
assumed debt.
   "This is a fairly significant acquisition for Amerada
Hess," said Bruce Lazier, an analyst with Prescott Ball &amp;
Turben Inc., New York. Mr. Lazier said the purchase is part
of an aggressive expansion plan by Amerada, which last
September acquired a big package of oil and gas assets in the
Gulf of Mexico from an affiliate of Houston's Transco Energy
Co., for $886 million.
   Poco, a modest but fast-growing oil and gas producer, said
its share of the purchase price is C$31.1 million, and the
transaction will ultimately result in it acquiring interests
in several properties in British Columbia and Alberta.
</TEXT>
