<HL>
   Who's News:
   Emulex Founder Cox
   Plans to Step Aside
   In Firm's Operations
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EMLX WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   COSTA MESA, Calif. -- Fred B. Cox, founder, chairman and
chief executive officer of Emulex Corp., said he plans to
relinquish daily operating responsibilities as the firm seeks
a new chief executive officer. David Hanna, a board member
and consultant, has been named interim president and will
assume day-to-day operating responsibility for the company.
   Mr. Cox said in a statement that he plans to remain
chairman and a board member, and will retain contact with the
company's key accounts. Mr. Cox founded Emulex in 1979, and
has spent 30 years in the electronics and computer industry.
The release didn't explain why Mr. Cox is stepping aside, and
company officials couldn't be reached for comment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Hanna spent 14 years with IBM in sales, marketing and
general management, and has served as chief executive officer
for several computer firms, including Altos Computer Systems
of San Jose, Calif.
   Emulex makes disk, tape and communications controllers for
peripheral computer equipment. For the 39 weeks ended April
1, Emulex reported a net loss of $2 million, or 19 cents a
share, on sales of $88 million.
</TEXT>
