<HL>
   The Outlook:
   Strength in Exports
   May Not Be Timely
   ----
   By Lindley H. Clark Jr.
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Ways and Means Committee recently
held a retreat on the subject of the Uruguay Round, the
latest multination effort to push the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade farther toward free and open world
commerce. C. Fred Bergsten, who moderated the session, said
the congressmen were skeptical about GATT. They thought
"Super 301," the system the U.S. uses to punish nations that
don't perform in world trade as the U.S. thinks they should,
is just great. Some of them seem to think a Super Duper 301
might be even better.
   Current trade statistics may have added to the feeling
that no new trade rules are needed. The Commerce Department
late last month raised its estimate of the first-quarter
gross national product because of a sharp upward adjustment
of exports. Exports slipped slightly in April, but imports
fell even more. So when Mr. Bergsten last week moderated
another conference, this one at his Institute for
International Economics, there was pessimism about the
chances of replacing America's unilateral trade policy with
an expanded multilateral approach.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last week Mr. Bergsten, in an understatement, told an
audience of academics, businessmen and government officials
that there was "some doubt" about the success of the Uruguay
Round. The talks are not scheduled to end until next
December, he noted, and international negotiations in the
past have always had aspects reminiscent of "The Perils of
Pauline" -- with victory finally being snatched from the jaws
of defeat. "But this time," he said, "we may be in more
trouble than usual."
                                                                                                       

   Carla Hills, the U.S. Trade Representative, told the
conference that President Bush at next week's Houston
economic summit will say that a successful Uruguay Round is
his most important economic objective. "It is beyond my
comprehension," she said, "that with so much at stake we
would not make the Uruguay Round work."
                                                                                                       

   It would be ironic to see the talks break down at a time
when, outside the negotiations, there seems to be momentum
toward free trade. The U.S. and Canada, after arguing about
their trade relations for more than a century, finally
concluded a free trade agreement. Mexico is talking about a
similar pact with the U.S. Brazil, long a strong
protectionist, last week announced it would lower tariffs and
ease import restrictions. Also last week, Mr. Bush proposed a
free-trade zone for the entire Western Hemisphere. The
nations of Eastern Europe, meanwhile, are hoping that
something like GATT will help them move toward economic
parity with the West.
   While failure of the round would be ironic, it is clearly
possible. A major U.S. goal in the current round is reform of
agricultural trade. The GATT nations have tried for reform
several times before, usually getting almost nowhere. "This
time," Dale-Hathaway, a consultant, said, "the talks seem to
be right on track." If there is a difference between the
current round and its predecessors, it could be that the
disagreements have increased.
   "Pressure at the economic summit won't help," Mr. Hathaway
said. "World leaders don't burden themselves with
agricultural problems."
                                                                                                       

   In the past the agricultural arguments have been "settled"
by postponing any difficult decisions to the next
multilateral meeting. But many of the developing countries
have a lot of agricultural goods they could sell if trade
restraints were reduced, and their support is needed if any
progress is to be made in several other areas. So failure in
agriculture could have broader effects.
                                                                                                       

   The current GATT round, for instance, is looking seriously
at services for the first time. The U.S., which is highly
efficient in services, wants the agreement to guarantee the
right to establish a business in a foreign country for the
purpose of providing a service. Several of the developing
countries would exclude any such provision. Brian Hindley of
the London School of Economics, who discussed the service
negotiations, said: "In a way, I'm an optimist. Unless the
whole round unravels, I think there will be an agreement on
trade in services. But the content of that agreement is far
from clear."
   Intellectual property is another area where the U.S. and
other industrial countries need support from the developing
world. The developed countries, as major exporters of
technology, want protection of trademarks, copyrights and
patents. Many developing countries, even if they agree with
protection in principle, lack either the will or the strength
to enforce it. The developing countries are hungry for
technology and tend to be leery of any rules that impede its
inflow.
                                                                                                       

   The issues are incredibly complex.
   One speaker last week argued that the time had come for a
thorough overhaul of the GATT organization. A major reason
for the U.S. move to unilateral settlement of trade disputes,
after all, is frustration with lengthy and uncertain GATT
dispute-settlement procedures.
                                                                                                       

   Meanwhile, many congressmen figure the U.S. is doing fine
with the status quo. How can the free traders convert
Congress? Henry R. Nau, a George Washington University
professor, suggests that the negotiators can do it by
bringing in a successful Uruguay Round agreement. Anyone who
listened to the talks last week knows that's a tough job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bruce Nobles, Head
   Of Trump Shuttle
   Steps Down From Post
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   X.TMP WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The head of the Trump Shuttle has stepped down, a move
reflecting the continuing turmoil at Donald Trump's
one-year-old airline.
   Bruce Nobles, president of the Shuttle, was replaced
Friday by Richard Cozzi, who has been the airline's vice
president of operations since its inception. Mr. Cozzi will
also be the chief operating officer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Shuttle has lost almost $100 million since Mr. Trump
acquired it from Eastern Airlines for $365 million in June
last year. Although Trump officials and Mr. Nobles weren't
available for comment, Mr. Trump has previously expressed
disappointment that the Shuttle hasn't performed better. The
airline, which operates Boston-New York-Washington shuttle
flights, has increased its share of that market to 50%, but
Trump officials had hoped for 60% by now.
   Mr. Nobles's departure follows a series of other changes
at the Trump Shuttle. It recently canceled four daily round
trips in both the Boston-New York and Washington-New York
markets on Saturday, as well as two other flights in each
market Sunday. Also, it has laid off about 70 employees and
cut back a few frills, such as its concierge desk.
   Mr. Nobles was president of the Pan Am Shuttle before
joining the Trump airline. At Pan Am, Mr. Nobles helped to
end Eastern Airlines' dominance in the lucrative Boston-New
York-Washington shuttle flights. By the end of 1988, after
two years of operations, Pan Am had garnered 45% of the
travel on those routes, largely because of Mr. Nobles's
start-up efforts and Eastern's much publicized difficulties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Lethal Weapon:
   Joel Silver Is Abrasive,
   Spends Extravagantly,
   But Makes Hit Movies
   ---
   He Completes `Die Hard 2'
   At a Cost of $62 Million;
   The Auditors Get Busy
   ---
   Crashing the Gates at Fox
   ----
   By Kathleen A. Hughes
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   NWS TWX PCI DIS
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOLLYWOOD -- Even in this town of flamboyant spenders,
37-year-old movie producer Joel Silver stands out.
   At an estimated cost of $62 million, his "Die Hard 2: Die
Harder," an extravaganza that opens on Wednesday, has become
one of the most expensive films ever made. "At one point we
thought we were spending $1 million a day," says Joe Roth,
chairman of News Corp.'s Twentieth Century Fox, the movie's
backer. "It was like walking down the street and finding a
hole in your pocket."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Silver has made others in Hollywood feel the same way.
His free-spending ways, along with his temper tantrums and
coarse manner, have alienated studio executives and
secretaries alike. But the success of his highly commercial
action movies such as "Predator" and "Lethal Weapon" has
redeemed him in the eyes of others.
   Spy magazine labeled him a "taste-free bullyboy." Actor
Rick Moranis parodied him as a fast-talking hysteric in the
movie "Head Office." Mr. Silver even played himself, a
screaming movie maker, in "Who Framed Roger Rabbit." But he
became the subject of gossip over the spending on "Die Hard
2," and Hollywood has been buzzing with stories of improper
use of studio funds.
   Mr. Silver declined to be interviewed. Through a
spokesman, he denies any wrongdoing. Fox itself insists that
a regular internal audit turned up no evidence of any
misappropriation of funds. Mr. Roth does say the studio has
increased its auditing staff as a result of the cost
overruns. The studio also took greater control of the set of
"Predator 2," produced by Mr. Silver and two other producers.
   "We are becoming more aggressive rather than reactive,"
says Mr. Roth. He adds: "Joel is an extravagant producer. He
is not irresponsible. He has a big appetite and a very wide
vision."
   He isn't the only one. A record year at the U.S. box
office and growing demand for American movies abroad have
loosened Hollywood's purse strings. Studios are spending
enormous sums on potential hits. Paramount Pictures' "Days of
Thunder" and Carolco's "Total Recall" each cost more than $50
million to produce.
   Mr. Silver's fans are quick to observe that, with various
partners, he has produced some of Hollywood's top-grossing
movies. With Richard Donner he made "Lethal Weapon 2," which
has grossed roughly $250 million. In February, the National
Association of Theater Owners named Mr. Silver producer of
the year, noting that revenues of films he helped produce had
topped $1 billion.
   Warner Brothers, which backed "Lethal Weapon" and its
sequel, also loves Mr. Silver. He recently signed a five-year
contract with the studio, which expects to back two or three
of his pictures a year. He commands one of Hollywood's
highest producer fees, $1 million a picture. He runs his
company, Silver Pictures, from a luxurious bungalow on the
Warner lot that once belonged to actress Marion Davies.
   Warner Brothers has even let Mr. Silver use one of its
jets to fly friends to his sprawling plantation in South
Carolina, where he is spending $2.5 million to renovate one
of the two Frank Lloyd Wright houses he owns. Actor Bruce
Willis, star of "Die Hard" and its sequel, and his wife, Demi
Moore, have been guests.
   "He is one of our most important producers," says Mark
Canton, an executive vice president of Warner Brothers, a
Time Warner division. "Joel Silver is as respected and
friendly with the cream of the crop of Hollywood as anyone I
know."
   But Mr. Silver's screaming matches have alienated senior
executives at several big studios, including Paramount and
Walt Disney Co. "Joel will let nothing stand in the way of
achieving his vision. You have to be prepared to battle him
along the way," says Leonard Goldberg, an independent
producer and a former head of Twentieth Century Fox who
worked with Mr. Silver on "Die Hard."
   Mr. Silver, son of a public-relations executive father and
a journalist mother, grew up in South Orange, N.J. An ardent
student of the old Hollywood, he attended New York University
film school. "Everyone else wanted to be a director,
cameraman or editor," recalls Jack Rapke, an agent at
Creative Artists Agency and a former classmate. "Joel had a
love affair with the Hollywood moguls. He aspired to be a
producer like David O. Selznick."
   He later took a job as an assistant to producer Larry
Gordon, a veteran maker of action movies. Friends say Mr.
Silver often served as Mr. Gordon's driver and seemed
desperate to succeed in the movie business; he coveted fine
clothes and possessions he couldn't yet afford. "He was
insanely hungry for money and power, but he didn't have
either, and that made him suffer," says Ken Finkleman, a
friend and the writer and director of "Head Office," the
movie that parodies Mr. Silver. "But his suffering was
endearing. He was funny and knew everything about Hollywood."
   Two of his attempts to leave Mr. Gordon and work within
other movie companies failed, partly because of his attitude
toward authority and spending. After he was hired as a
production executive at Universal Pictures in March of 1979,
he bought art deco furniture for his office and sent the
company a bill for more than $6,500. Insiders at the time say
top executives were stunned because he hadn't asked for
permission first. The company ordered him to pay the bill
himself.
   Mr. Silver also threw a birthday party for himself at
Michael's, a pricey restaurant in Santa Monica. He invited
about 40 guests, including Universal executives. He later
submitted an expense accounting for more than $10,000.
Insiders at the time say the company again told him to pay
up. They say he was fired after less than a year in January
of 1980. While there, he had supervised "Xanadu," one of
Universal's biggest bombs, an over-budget musical starring
Olivia Newton John.
   Mr. Silver had another brief tenure, at Polygram Pictures,
run at the time by producers Peter Guber and Jon Peters. He
was brought in by Mr. Guber as an executive vice president of
development and production in April of 1981. He left less
than two months later after repeated clashes with Mr. Peters.
"Sparks flew," recalls Gordon Stulberg, who was president of
the company at the time.
   There were other problems, including spending on the movie
"The Pursuit of D.B. Cooper," which Mr. Silver was asked to
help salvage. Frank Baur, vice president and executive
production manager at the time, says Mr. Silver asked him to
"conceal or delay the reporting on the spending." Mr. Baur
says he refused. He also recalls that Mr. Silver said, "No
{expletive} hairdresser is going to tell me what to do,"
referring to Mr. Peters' former occupation.
   Fred Altman, Mr. Silver's business manager, says Mr.
Baur's statement about concealing spending is "ludicrous." A
lawyer for Mr. Silver, Jake Bloom, says the producer left
both Universal Pictures and Polygram by "mutual consent." He
also says that when Mr. Silver moved to Polygram, that
company agreed to purchase his art deco furniture from
Universal, and when Mr. Silver left Polygram, he bought it
back as part of his settlement.
   Mr. Silver returned to Mr. Gordon and has worked with him
on and off ever since. Their first big hit was "48 Hours," an
action movie starring Eddie Murphy that grossed about $100
million. But Mr. Silver and Mr. Gordon have since had their
share of disappointments, such as "Streets of Fire," a big
money loser for Universal. Some of Mr. Silver's attempts to
produce movies on his own didn't fare particularly well at
the box office, such as "Road House" and "Weird Science."
   Mr. Gordon remains the senior partner, and his producer
credit comes first on Gordon-Silver films such as "Die Hard"
and its sequel. But it is Mr. Silver who usually spends long
hours on the set. Unlike many producers, he deeply involves
himself in every stage of a movie, from script development
through final editing. He has aggressively pursued stars such
as Arnold Schwarzenegger for his movies. "No one fights
harder to get a movie made," says Mr. Gordon.
   Some people think he fights too hard. His aggressiveness
has led him to bulldoze anything that stands in his way --
sometimes almost literally.
   Stalled by a line of cars at the Fox studio guard gate
during the filming of "Die Hard," he once ordered the driver
of his Mercedes-Benz to enter at the exit. An irate Fox
official ripped the identification decal off his car and
banned Mr. Silver from the lot. Mr. Goldberg finally decided
to ban only the car and driver. "It sounds like a childish
solution but I was anxious to get him back," says Mr.
Goldberg.
   People who stand in his way sometimes suffer his wrath. An
official of the Los Angeles airport once ordered Mr. Silver
to come up with a $100,000 deposit to continue filming
"Commando" after a spat over moving an X-ray machine. "He
told me how important he was, and he said he would have my
head," says Lang Moy, assistant to the chief of airport
operations. "I thought he had an ego problem. I guess he
feels very impressed with himself. He feels he can buy and
sell people."
   Mr. Silver's Rambo-style personality seems suited to the
action genre. For a scene in the original "Die Hard," he even
pressed to create a real explosion on a lower floor of Fox
Plaza, a major Los Angeles office building then owned by Fox.
"He promised he could get it cleaned up and the windows back
in over the weekend," says Craig Baumgarten, executive vice
president of production at Fox at the time. Fox overruled Mr.
Silver and the scene was filmed in miniature with scale
models.
   Fox itself is partly to blame for the cost of making "Die
Hard 2." Mr. Roth, who joined Fox last August, didn't decide
until October to rush the movie into production for summer
release. That gave the crew little time to prepare for the
big-scale airport thriller, which requires snow scenes. Mr.
Silver led the hapless crew of more than 200 from one city to
another in search of snow as weather forecasts failed them.
Mr. Roth received bills as high as $50,000 for dry ice and
$100,000 a day for the use of a Boeing 747.
   As the costs escalated, worried Fox executives looked for
ways to save money, and Mr. Silver kept fighting for scenes
he wanted. "I was getting phone calls at midnight," says
Roger Birnbaum, president of production at Fox. Mr. Silver,
he recalls, would typically say, "You're killing me] You're
killing me] I'm out here and I'm going to give you a $100
million movie. If you don't give me this, the movie will be a
flop. It will be on your shoulders]"
   During the filming, Mr. Silver helped to organize a
birthday party for Mr. Willis, the movie's star, at a bowling
alley in Studio City. Those on the invitation list, including
Sylvester Stallone and Eddie Murphy, received bowling shirts
with their names embroidered above the pockets, by messenger.
The party cost about $10,000, which didn't come from the
movie's budget. It was paid for by Mr. Silver, Twentieth
Century Fox, Warner Brothers, Tri-Star Pictures and Triad
Artists, a talent management agency.
   Still, as the movie's cost kept climbing, Fox's largess
waned. Fox sent John Landau, a new senior executive vice
president of production, and Tom Jacobson, executive vice
president, to the sets of both "Die Hard 2" and "Predator 2"
to control costs. "As the picture became more difficult, we
asked to be involved in any decision that wasn't in the
budget," says Mr. Jacobson. "They were big money decisions."
   Insiders say Fox executives are now unlikely to pursue
three additional projects they have in development with Mr.
Silver. But "Ford Fairlane," another Fox movie produced by
Mr. Silver, is expected to be released this summer.
   While the cost of the movie may have dismayed Fox, Mr.
Silver's spending habits clearly please his crews. "The
difference between working for Joel and another producer is
the difference between flying baggage and first class," says
Nancy Hansen, a script supervisor. "His caterer serves
Chateaubriand steak that is so tender you can cut it with a
plastic fork."
   Mr. Silver, who collects pottery and Frank Lloyd
Wright-designed furniture, once told a gathering of studio
executives, "I'm not in this business to make art. I'm in
this business to make money to buy art." Six years ago he
paid about $726,000 for the Storer house, a concrete-block
home in the fashionable Hollywood Hills designed by Mr.
Wright in the 1920s. Its restoration has been chronicled in
House &amp; Garden.
   His greatest indulgence may be the Auldbrass Plantation on
more than 200 acres in South Carolina. As part of his $2.5
million renovation, he added a 135-foot swimming pool and a
tennis court. He is also rebuilding the stable, where he
keeps a white Arabian horse, a gift from singer Wayne Newton.
A cook prepares southern dishes such as alligator and key
lime pie for guests.
   His plans proved too grand for friends who bought the
house with him three years ago, and Mr. Silver bought them
out.
   A female associate suggests that Mr. Silver be nicknamed
"Citizen Silver" after the movie based on the life of William
Randolph Hearst, the publishing magnate who built the opulent
California castle called San Simeon. Mr. Silver's Auldbrass
Plantation, says Michael Levy, president of Silver Pictures,
"will be his San Simeon."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Quarterly Review of Underwriting:
   Underwriting
   Fees in 1st Half
   At 5-Year Low
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   MER AXP SLH GE ABSB SB MS PWJ
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- When it comes to underwriting stocks and
bonds, more is less these days on Wall Street.
   Despite a rising volume of new issues, securities firms'
underwriting profits in the first half plunged to their
lowest level in five years. Fees that firms earned from
underwriting new securities so far this year amounted to a
paltry $1.2 billion, according to Securities Data Co. That's
down 17% from a year earlier -- even though the volume of new
issues actually rose 13% in the same period.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The reason is that Wall Street firms are making less than
ever on each stock or bond issue they help bring to market.
The fee that securities firms raked in for each issue -- an
average of $399,000 -- is down 44% from a year earlier. In
1985, the last time total underwriting fees were so lean,
Wall Street firms made an average of $1.1 million an issue,
Securities Data says.
   "This is just a dramatic drop-off," says Francine Wissak,
a Securities Data analyst. The shrinking fees per issue
should throw cold water on "anyone who says they're doing
deals and making money and that things are coming back to
normal levels," Ms. Wissak says.
   The deepening slump in underwriting profits is likely to
lead Wall Street firms to cut staffs further and pay many of
the remaining employees less, some industry executives argue.
Even as underwriting fees slump to five-year lows, salaries
remain far above 1985 levels.
   "We've got to be more rational on compensation," says
Robert Downey, a partner at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. and chairman
of the Securities Industry Association, a trade group. Wall
Streeters "can have damn good careers," Mr. Downey says, "but
they're not going to have instant gratification."
   The end of Wall Street's fat-fee era reflects the collapse
of the junk-bond market, once a big money maker for
investment banks. Just seven new junk-bond issues were
brought to market in this year's first half, with fees
totaling a mere $16.2 million. This is down from $462.4
million in fees for 69 issues a year earlier, Securities Data
says. Throughout the late 1980s, junk bond fees averaged $450
million every six months.
   Despite lower fees paid by issuers, some securities
executives maintain that underwriting profitability has
rebounded in other areas. They say that's partly because
firms are widening the underwriting "spread," or the
difference between the price a securities firm pays to buy an
issue of stock or bonds from the issuing company and the
slightly higher price the firm charges investors.
   "In the past, much of the spread has been given up to the
investor, and investment bankers haven't kept it," says Roger
Vasey, senior vice president of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.'s global
debt markets division. "Now the trend is in favor of
retaining a bigger percentage of the spread on deals,
although we're working harder for it."
   Still, there's currently nothing in Wall Street's hopper
to replace the once-lush revenue flowing from high-yield junk
bonds. For instance, the hottest area of the underwriting
landscape right now -- mortgage and asset-backed securities
-- generates razor-thin fees for securities firms, industry
executives say.
   One area that's making up ground is fees from underwriting
issues of common -- both initial public offerings and issues
by companies with stock outstanding. With the stock market
rising to near-record levels and many companies trying to
reduce debt levels by selling equity, fees earned from
underwriting stocks surged 35% to $709.3 million in the first
half, Securities Data says.
   Some analysts expect the stock resurgence to continue. "As
companies de-leverage going into the '90s, you should have
more issuance of stock to strengthen {the companies'} capital
structures," says James Hanbury, an analyst at Wertheim
Schroder &amp; Co.
   Goldman Sachs was swept up by the rising equity tide.
Goldman ranked No. 2 in total underwriting fees for stocks
and bonds for the six months, earning $171.7 million in fees,
nearly two-thirds of it from stock issues. Merrill Lynch,
with $172.6 million in fees, remained on top, underwriting 29
more stock or debt issues than Goldman.
   Initial public stock offerings, although not booming,
continued to rake in the fees. Securities firms' fees from
IPOs totaled $457 million, a 15% jump from $396 million in
the first half of 1989. Although IPOs account for 40% of all
underwriting fees, they're still far below the levels seen
just a few years back. In 1986's fourth quarter alone, IPOs
generated $541 million in fees for Wall Street, surpassing
this year's entire first-half level.
   Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc., helped by heavy IPO volume,
jumped to the No. 3 fee spot for total underwriting fees. The
Baltimore-based brokerage firm earned $114.3 million in fees
through 22 offerings -- a big jump from its $63.9 million and
its No. 9 ranking in last year's first half. Much of the
increase stems from a threefold jump in IPOs underwritten by
Alex. Brown.
   "The markets have been more receptive," says Richard
Franyo, an Alex. Brown managing director. "But you've got to
be a bit worried that as the markets get a little overcooked,
it could end."
   Salomon Brothers Inc. ranked No. 4, posting a 65% jump in
underwriting fees for the period. But First Boston Corp. and
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. lost ground. First Boston, which
has shied away from the junk market recently, made just $89.5
million in total underwriting fees, down 22% from a year
earlier. Shearson Lehman slipped to the No. 8 spot from No.
5, earning $78.6 million. Shearson was hurt in part by
uncertainty stemming from the firm's well-publicized
financial and management turmoil.
   Missing in action is Wall Street's fee leader for 1989's
first half. Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. earned $260 million
from underwritings, with junk bonds accounting for 94% of its
fee total. Of course, Drexel is out of the picture now; its
parent company filed for bankruptcy-law protection in
February after a cash crunch caused by the collapse of the
junk-bond market.
   ---
