<HL>
   International Brief -- Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.:
   Acquisition of 25.1% Stake
   In West German Firm Set
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. of Japan said it agreed
to acquire a 25.1% equity stake in Loewe Opta G.m.b.H., a
West German maker of consumer electronic products. Terms
weren't disclosed.
   "By becoming a partner with Loewe, Matsushita would like
to form an industrial partnership with the German company
involving a joint development of digital TV and other areas
of color TV production," said Tadakazu Yamamoto, a Matsushita
managing director in charge of the company's color television
sector.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita officials said acquiring the Loewe stake is
part of Matsushita's program to increase its overseas
production to 50% of its entire business outside Japan by
1993. Matsushita already operates 18 overseas plants in 15
countries for TV production; it makes TV sets in Britain.
   Loewe, established in 1923 and capitalized at 45 million
marks ($26.9 million), makes color TV sets, car electronic
equipment and telecommunications products. It has about 1,500
employees and had 1989 sales of 300 million marks, Matsushita
officials said.
</TEXT>
