<HL>
   Arco Hits Snag
   In Acquisition
   Of Carbide Lines
   ----
   By Richard Koenig
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   UK RCM ARC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Federal Trade Commission took a step toward blocking
the $220 million acquisition of certain assets of Union
Carbide Corp. by Arco Chemical Co., but the companies said
they believe they can still resolve antitrust issues.
   Resolving those issues may be particularly important to
Arco Chemical, because it has already made full payment to
Carbide. And, according to both companies, the payment is
nonrefundable under the terms of their agreement, reached
last September. The companies added that if the deal doesn't
go through, Arco Chemical has rights to the proceeds from a
subsequent sale of the assets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The step taken by the FTC was to authorize its staff to
seek a preliminary injunction rescinding Arco Chemical's
purchase of Carbide's urethane polyols and propylene glycol
businesses. Urethane polyols are the main raw material for
polyurethane, which is used in foam cushions and packaging.
Propylene glycol is used in products including fiberglass,
paints and cosmetics.
   The FTC said it was seeking a recision, as opposed to a
barring of the transaction, because it "had reason to believe
that beneficial ownership" of Carbide's assets had already
passed to Arco Chemical. Marc Schildkraut, an FTC staff
member, declined to say exactly what constitutes beneficial
ownership in the view of the commission. But he acknowledged
that the up-front payment by Arco Chemical is part of the
issue.
   "An up-front payment is unusual," said Mr. Schildkraut.
Asked whether the payment could be returned to Arco Chemical
by court order, he said, "That's something that will be up to
the judge." The companies haven't commented on the reasons
for the terms of the agreement.
   The FTC also alleged that the companies failed to make
timely premerger notification filings to antitrust agencies.
The commission didn't go into specifics, and the companies
denied the charge.
   A spokesman for Carbide, based in Danbury, Conn., said it
continues to operate the businesses in question and to
collect the revenue from them. Upon closing of the sale, he
said, Carbide is to pay Arco Chemical any "surplus cash flow"
accumulated during this interim period, and Arco Chemical is
to compensate Carbide for any "negative cash flow."
   Carbide has already accounted for the up-front payment,
having taken in the 1989 third quarter a gain to earnings of
about $62 million.
   Arco Chemical, based in Newtown Square, Pa., said in a
statement that it is still negotiating with the FTC's staff
and that the commission's action "was intended only to
authorize litigation in the event the matter cannot otherwise
be resolved."
   All the parties to the negotiations declined to specify
the antitrust issues.
   Arco Chemical added that it is confident the courts will
allow the acquisition to proceed if the FTC's action results
in litigation.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Arco
Chemical closed at $40.75, unchanged. The company is
83%-owned by Atlantic Richfield Co., Los Angeles. Carbide
shares closed on the Big Board at $19.25, down 12.5 cents
apiece.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900702-0033
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900702-0033.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Mellon Foundation to Give
   Land to U.S. Government
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- A foundation here plans to donate 100,000
acres of historic and ecologically sensitive land to the
federal government in what appears to be the largest such
gift ever.
   The land, which was acquired over the past two years for
$21 million, includes a 93,000-acre wildlife refuge in North
Carolina and the so-called "Cornfield" at Antietam National
Battlefield in Maryland, site of one of the bloodiest Civil
War battles.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The gift by the Richard King Mellon Foundation is a rare
show of environmental philanthropy. Only 3.6% of all
foundation grant money goes to the environment, according to
the Foundation Center in New York, which tracks foundation
grants.
   The Mellon Foundation, a leader in environmental
philanthropy, purchased the properties through The
Conservation Fund, an Arlington, Va.-based non-profit group.
The fund selected the land from a government list of
ecological and historical properties, many of which were
threatened by commercial development. The conservation
organization benefited from a sluggish real estate market,
but often found itself competing with land developers.
   The fund, for example, paid $8.8 million for the
93,000-acre wildlife refuge in Alligator River, N.C.,
outbidding a group of Japanese investors who wanted to mine
the land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
