<HL>
   Treasury, in Switch, Finds
   No Glitch in Mexico Bonds
</HL>
<DATE>
07/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- After recently saying that its discovery of
a glitch in accounting for zero-coupon bonds sold to Mexico
had caused an immediate jump of $27 billion in debt subject
to the federal debt ceiling, the Treasury has concluded that
there was no glitch.
   A Treasury spokesman, acknowledging "some confusion" in
statutory interpretation, said the department's lawyers have
now determined the initial interpretation was the correct
one. The ruling involved $30 billion in zero-coupons bonds
sold to Mexico earlier this year to help that country
alleviate its debt problem.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The latest shift, however, doesn't alter the Treasury's
need for an increase in its current $3.12 trillion debt limit
before Congress starts its scheduled August recess. Without
an increase before the recess, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady warned Congress in a recent letter, "it is highly
likely that default would occur before Congress returns in
September."
   Mr. Brady stressed that debt ceilings estimates are
subject to greater-than-usual uncertainty now because the
Resolution Trust Corp. is borrowing working capital from the
Federal Financing Bank, an entity within Treasury. His letter
didn't mention the zero-coupon bonds.
</TEXT>
